              <p>Wes Anderson’s ‘The Grand Budapest Hotel’ and James Gray’s ‘The Immigrant’ are period fantasies that shy away from real Jews. They may lack the essential pintele yid, but that doesn’t make them any less Jew-ish.
</p>
              <p><strong>Source:</strong> J. Hoberman, tabletmag.com</p>
